<div id="review_716464831" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/716464831" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7282028-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1325556945p2/7282028.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/716464831?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/7282028-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer716464831" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2222343092895377832">Charmed by the title, I found I had to push myself a little to read all the way through this book. Presenting British colonials desperate to farm in Northern Rhodesia under Ian Smith, the author (their child) manages to maintain a nice balance between understanding her parents&apos; desires and quirks, madness and grief, while also fully comprehending what the consequences of their actions (and others&apos;) were to African natives. Reading it is an easy way to learn a little about the history of southern</span>
  <span id="freeText2222343092895377832" style="display:none">Charmed by the title, I found I had to push myself a little to read all the way through this book. Presenting British colonials desperate to farm in Northern Rhodesia under Ian Smith, the author (their child) manages to maintain a nice balance between understanding her parents' desires and quirks, madness and grief, while also fully comprehending what the consequences of their actions (and others') were to African natives. Reading it is an easy way to learn a little about the history of southern Africa, the Boers, the British, the Mau Mau, Mozambique rebels, and the various and innumerable ways human beings can first construe differences among each other as rendering groups of people as beings of a lesser order, and then committing atrocities on each other "to protect their way of life" or to "liberate" themselves. In spite of this, the book is a fairly light read, though the author sometimes makes an observation so true that it takes your breath away, like the following: "No one starts a war warning that those involved with lose their innocence--that children will definitely die and be forever lost as a result of the conflict; that the war will not end for generations and generations, even after cease-fires have been declared and peace treaties have been signed. No one starts a war that way, but they should. It would at least be fair warning and an honest admission: even a good war--if there is such a thing--will kill anyone old enough to die." (p. 196)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2222343092895377832" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


