    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_484035807" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/484035807" />
    <a title="C.G. Worrell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6159855-c-g-worrell"><img alt="C.G. Worrell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1314657932p2/6159855.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/484035807?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="C.G. Worrell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="C.G. Worrell" href="/user/show/6159855-c-g-worrell">C.G. Worrell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer484035807" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1796044306007786163">While perusing the shelves of Barnes &amp; Noble, I came across this book. The title and cover photo immediately hooked me. This memoir largely centers around the life of &quot;Nicola Fuller of Central Africa&quot;, the eccentric mother of the author. For fifty years, we follow this pukka-pukka-sahib (most excellent mistress) and her family as political conditions and war force the Fullers from Kenya to Rhodesia to Malawi, and finally, Zambia where they run a banana and fish farm. Nicola is clearly a hypomani</span>
  <span id="freeText1796044306007786163" style="display:none">While perusing the shelves of Barnes &amp; Noble, I came across this book. The title and cover photo immediately hooked me. This memoir largely centers around the life of "Nicola Fuller of Central Africa", the eccentric mother of the author. For fifty years, we follow this pukka-pukka-sahib (most excellent mistress) and her family as political conditions and war force the Fullers from Kenya to Rhodesia to Malawi, and finally, Zambia where they run a banana and fish farm. Nicola is clearly a hypomanic whose world view and illusions of grandeur keep the reader engaged and giggling. Nicola blossoms from an enchanted land where a little girl can truly have a chimpanzee as a best friend (and that's just the start of the zaniness). But Africa has its dark sides: war, strife, disease, snakes, and loss. These forces take their toll on the family and Nicola's soul. Even so, her indomitable spirit gathers strength from the Tree of Forgetfulness, the heart of her current home in Zambia. I'd love to share a cocktail with this woman as she sits surrounded by her pack of dogs. She has seen and done so much.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1796044306007786163" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

